528
00:30:56.734 --> 00:30:59.694
Early Detection Research Network, or EDRN for short.

529
00:31:00.714 --> 00:31:02.814
I do not have any relevant disclosures.

530
00:31:03.914 --> 00:31:07.754
So before I go into the details of our work, I think it's important to take a

531
00:31:07.794 --> 00:31:10.234
little bit of a step back and talk about our overall approach,

532
00:31:11.034 --> 00:31:14.934
because the development of blood-based biomarkers for really any kind of

533
00:31:14.974 --> 00:31:18.634
context has historically been hampered by issues

534
00:31:18.714 --> 00:31:22.334
related to reproducibility, and so it is critical to employ

535
00:31:22.394 --> 00:31:25.974
rigorous study designs to be able to achieve our translational

536
00:31:26.054 --> 00:31:30.014
goals. And very early on, when I started doing work in this space, I had the good

537
00:31:30.054 --> 00:31:32.934
fortune of collaborating with Dr. Margaret Pepe.

538
00:31:33.714 --> 00:31:37.564
She is a now retired biostatistician who spent decades working

539
00:31:37.834 --> 00:31:41.754
at Fred Hutch. And she really led the development of

540
00:31:41.774 --> 00:31:45.524
building out a robust framework for the evaluation of candidate biomarkers,

541
00:31:46.034 --> 00:31:48.034
particularly in the cancer setting.

542
00:31:48.134 --> 00:31:51.934
And her approach really continues to be the gold standard used by

543
00:31:51.974 --> 00:31:55.874
EDRN investigators today. And while I scoured the internet, I could not find a

544
00:31:55.914 --> 00:31:59.294
single photo of her online. I think that she would appreciate instead

545
00:31:59.914 --> 00:32:03.874
me highlighting one of her seminal papers in this space that she

546
00:32:03.934 --> 00:32:05.514
published back in 2008,

547
00:32:06.994 --> 00:32:10.954
that again, laid out a number of these key principles that biomarker studies

548
00:32:10.994 --> 00:32:14.334
need to follow. So the first thing is that this

549
00:32:15.014 --> 00:32:17.894
framework is called the PROBE design, which stands for Prospective Specimen

550
00:32:17.994 --> 00:32:20.964
Collection, Retrospective Blinded Evaluation.

551
00:32:21.514 --> 00:32:23.514
And it really starts out by laying

552
00:32:24.414 --> 00:32:27.454
that people who are designing these types of biomarkers

553
00:32:28.614 --> 00:32:32.274
need to very clearly think through what are the potential clinical applications

554
00:32:32.314 --> 00:32:35.774
that the biomarkers are intended for. What is the target population?

555
00:32:36.294 --> 00:32:38.814
What is the setting in which patients would receive this test?

556
00:32:39.074 --> 00:32:42.454
And what would be the outcome of interest that is being tracked?

557
00:32:42.494 --> 00:32:46.454
And then once you have set out the clinical application, you can then define

558
00:32:46.494 --> 00:32:49.774
what are the necessary performance characteristics in terms of sensitivity and

559
00:32:49.854 --> 00:32:53.574
specificity that the test would need to have in order to achieve

560
00:32:53.914 --> 00:32:55.224
the desired clinical utility.

561
00:32:56.454 --> 00:33:00.014
She also really prioritized the use of what we call preclinical samples.

562
00:33:00.034 --> 00:33:03.884
So these are samples that are drawn from healthy patients prior to their

563
00:33:03.914 --> 00:33:07.874
diagnosis of cancer. In this field today, many people are

564
00:33:07.914 --> 00:33:09.974
still using convenient sets of samples.

565
00:33:10.014 --> 00:33:13.824
These are samples that are drawn from newly diagnosed cancer patients and then

566
00:33:13.854 --> 00:33:17.664
compared to whatever sort of set of normal, healthy individuals that are

567
00:33:17.734 --> 00:33:20.754
out there, and there can just be issues in the way those samples were collected

568
00:33:20.794 --> 00:33:21.854
that lead to differences.

569
00:33:23.234 --> 00:33:27.023
And so using rigorously collected preclinical samples

570
00:33:27.154 --> 00:33:30.994
really mirrors the intended clinical application, because you're

571
00:33:31.074 --> 00:33:34.794
using samples that are from patients who don't have clinically

572
00:33:34.834 --> 00:33:36.914
detectable cancer at the time that the blood was drawn.

573
00:33:37.974 --> 00:33:41.754
Of course, it's important to utilize rigorous study designs

574
00:33:42.054 --> 00:33:45.754
and have stringent study protocols for the way that the specimens were

575
00:33:45.794 --> 00:33:48.934
collected, processed, and stored, and then to use

576
00:33:49.334 --> 00:33:51.504
laboratory tools that are both reproducible

577
00:33:52.754 --> 00:33:56.324
and can be validated. We have also prioritized the use of

578
00:33:56.354 --> 00:33:59.894
platforms where the volumes of samples that are required are small

579
00:33:59.914 --> 00:34:03.434
because we're largely using very precious samples from various

580
00:34:03.474 --> 00:34:06.854
prospective cohort studies, where we're only able to get very

581
00:34:07.154 --> 00:34:09.814
small volumes of samples for testing.

582
00:34:10.274 --> 00:34:13.915
And then depending on the context, it may be critically important to also

583
00:34:13.935 --> 00:34:15.455
incorporate disease heterogeneity.

584
00:34:15.534 --> 00:34:17.915
So the work that I'm going to present is on breast cancer.

585
00:34:18.455 --> 00:34:22.254
I think we appreciate that there are major molecular subtypes of breast

586
00:34:22.274 --> 00:34:25.834
cancer that have very different underlying biologies.

587
00:34:26.154 --> 00:34:29.574
So we would fully expect then that the types of early detection

588
00:34:29.594 --> 00:34:33.034
biomarkers for, say, luminal hormone receptor-positive breast

589
00:34:33.114 --> 00:34:36.274
cancer might be completely different from those for

590
00:34:36.374 --> 00:34:39.214
triple-negative basal-like breast cancer.

591
00:34:39.225 --> 00:34:42.554
And so that's one way we've tried to account for this disease heterogeneity.

592
00:34:43.234 --> 00:34:46.873
Another framework that Margaret developed that we are also using in our work

593
00:34:47.534 --> 00:34:51.415
are these so-called five phases of biomarker discovery and validation.

594
00:34:51.754 --> 00:34:55.214
Basically, biomarkers would have to pass each of these steps

595
00:34:55.534 --> 00:34:58.634
sequentially in order to ultimately achieve clinical utility.

596
00:34:58.714 --> 00:35:02.014
So it starts with Phase I studies, which are really preclinical

597
00:35:02.074 --> 00:35:05.854
exploratory studies, all the way through to Phase V studies, which are generally

598
00:35:05.934 --> 00:35:09.254
randomized controlled trials, where you're really evaluating the

599
00:35:09.674 --> 00:35:10.254
efficacy

600
00:35:11.114 --> 00:35:13.234
and efficiency of the particular test that you

601
00:35:14.134 --> 00:35:18.074
have developed. The work that I'm going to be describing today are our results

602
00:35:18.174 --> 00:35:22.154
with respect to Phase II and Phase III studies, and then also

603
00:35:22.214 --> 00:35:25.474
our planned upcoming Phase IV prospective study.

604
00:35:25.534 --> 00:35:29.194
So that's kind of what my talk will cover, is that scope of work.

605
00:35:30.234 --> 00:35:32.374
So okay. So now kind of turning to

606
00:35:33.814 --> 00:35:35.954
breast cancer and the work that we will be doing.

607
00:35:36.054 --> 00:35:39.994
So I think as Graham clearly outlined, mammography is

608
00:35:40.054 --> 00:35:43.994
widely utilized. It has been shown in randomized controlled trials

609
00:35:44.034 --> 00:35:47.534
to reduce mortality by 30% among women 50 to

610
00:35:47.754 --> 00:35:48.834
69 years of age.

611
00:35:49.734 --> 00:35:51.774
But mammography has certain limitations.

612
00:35:51.894 --> 00:35:55.154
Its positive predictive value is only 4.4%.

613
00:35:55.164 --> 00:35:58.334
That does improve among older women.

614
00:35:58.934 --> 00:36:02.764
But breast cancer screening remains an important public health challenge

615
00:36:02.834 --> 00:36:06.614
because breast cancer remains the leading cause of cancer mortality among women

616
00:36:06.634 --> 00:36:10.284
worldwide. So our goal is really to try to develop biomarkers that can

617
00:36:10.314 --> 00:36:14.094
improve mammography's performance, and we've also already talked about some of the

618
00:36:14.234 --> 00:36:18.214
areas for improvement. So one is that mammography has a relatively high

619
00:36:18.294 --> 00:36:22.094
recall rate of 10%, meaning 10% of all women who go for screening

620
00:36:22.134 --> 00:36:25.974
mammogram are asked to come back for a repeat testing of one type or

621
00:36:25.994 --> 00:36:29.954
another. But only five out of every 100 women who come back for that

622
00:36:29.974 --> 00:36:33.846
repeat testing are diagnosed with cancer.We also have talked about

623
00:36:33.856 --> 00:36:36.006
this challenge of interval-detected cancers.

624
00:36:36.246 --> 00:36:40.156
About 20% of breast cancers are detected in

625
00:36:40.206 --> 00:36:41.606
that interval between

626
00:36:42.686 --> 00:36:45.626
regular screening mammograms, and so this is certainly an issue.

627
00:36:46.066 --> 00:36:49.346
And there also remain a number of other ongoing controversies with mammography in

628
00:36:49.386 --> 00:36:53.026
terms of when to start screening, when to stop screening, and whether or not

629
00:36:53.046 --> 00:36:53.286
certain

630
00:36:54.586 --> 00:36:55.976
subgroups of women should be prioritized.

631
00:36:56.006 --> 00:36:58.246
And Graham very nicely laid out a lot of these issues.

632
00:36:59.026 --> 00:37:02.946
So for the work that I'm going to be talking about, we really focused on the age

633
00:37:03.026 --> 00:37:06.226
range of women where there's sort of very little controversy, I would say, around

634
00:37:06.346 --> 00:37:10.106
screening women 50 to 69. And we also know that in this age range,

635
00:37:10.166 --> 00:37:14.106
about 80% of breast cancers that are diagnosed are hormone receptor positive, so we

636
00:37:14.126 --> 00:37:17.686
really focused on developing biomarkers specific for hormone receptor

637
00:37:17.786 --> 00:37:18.886
positive disease.

638
00:37:20.346 --> 00:37:24.046
Okay. So, as Margaret had laid out for us, we needed to

639
00:37:24.086 --> 00:37:27.335
define what our intended clinical application. So we have three of them.

640
00:37:27.386 --> 00:37:31.166
In the interest of time, I'm only going to be talking about the first one, which is

641
00:37:31.206 --> 00:37:35.056
to inform the timing of a subsequent mammogram in women who've had a negative

642
00:37:35.126 --> 00:37:38.926
screening mammogram. So basically, a woman comes in, she has a mammogram,

643
00:37:39.026 --> 00:37:42.486
it's negative. Can we then do a test that would say, "Okay, you're at high risk.

644
00:37:42.546 --> 00:37:45.686
You should actually come back early for another screening mammogram in, say, six

645
00:37:45.726 --> 00:37:49.256
months. You're at average risk. You can come back in one to two years, or maybe

646
00:37:49.256 --> 00:37:53.086
you're very low risk, and you can come back more than two years later." So

647
00:37:53.146 --> 00:37:57.066
that is kind of the application I'm going to be talking about today.

648
00:37:57.386 --> 00:38:00.066
So we then had to define, well, what would be the necessary performance

649
00:38:00.146 --> 00:38:02.446
characteristics for a test of this type to be useful?

650
00:38:03.446 --> 00:38:06.666
And so, kind of forgive me in advance, but I'm going to kind of go through some of

651
00:38:06.706 --> 00:38:08.526
the details of the math that's involved here.

652
00:38:09.406 --> 00:38:12.826
This really started with saying, "Okay, among women 50 to

653
00:38:13.026 --> 00:38:17.006
69, what is the annual instance rate of breast cancer for those who've just had a

654
00:38:17.026 --> 00:38:19.776
negative screening mammogram?" It's about 0.3%.

655
00:38:20.206 --> 00:38:23.916
So if we think about this context of early recall in six months, we can

656
00:38:23.946 --> 00:38:27.626
assume that then the instance rate at six months would be

657
00:38:27.646 --> 00:38:31.466
0.15%. So this is obviously a very low percent, but that's

658
00:38:31.786 --> 00:38:33.946
what we can then base our calculations off of.

659
00:38:35.166 --> 00:38:38.756
So given this context of a very low incidence rate and

660
00:38:38.786 --> 00:38:42.706
the screening context, we decided that we wanted to have a test with

661
00:38:42.786 --> 00:38:46.426
a very high specificity. In other words, a very low false

662
00:38:46.466 --> 00:38:50.326
positive rate of only 5%. We then evaluated, okay, given

663
00:38:50.346 --> 00:38:54.266
that very high specificity, what would we be able to detect with different levels

664
00:38:54.306 --> 00:38:56.066
of sensitivity or true positive rate?

665
00:38:56.146 --> 00:38:59.926
So at 35% sensitivity, we would detect 10 and a half breast

666
00:39:00.006 --> 00:39:03.126
cancers for every 1,000 repeat six-month mammograms.

667
00:39:03.586 --> 00:39:07.266
If we set it even lower to only 20%, we would detect six for

668
00:39:07.446 --> 00:39:09.386
1,000 repeat six-month mammograms.

669
00:39:09.826 --> 00:39:11.546
So what do these numbers mean?

670
00:39:12.406 --> 00:39:14.626
Would this be good? Would this be bad? Is this helpful or not?

671
00:39:15.026 --> 00:39:17.586
Fortunately, we have the context of mammography itself,

672
00:39:18.386 --> 00:39:18.646
which

673
00:39:19.486 --> 00:39:22.986
detects three and a half cancers for every 1,000 regular screening mammograms.

674
00:39:23.026 --> 00:39:26.566
So actually, this level of performance actually exceeds the performance of

675
00:39:26.586 --> 00:39:28.126
mammography itself. So we thought, okay,

676
00:39:30.026 --> 00:39:33.956
if we're, again, setting this high specificity of 95%, we could actually

677
00:39:33.986 --> 00:39:37.436
tolerate a test with relatively low sensitivity, even in the 20% to

678
00:39:37.446 --> 00:39:41.386
35% range. So that was what we set as our desired minimally acceptable

679
00:39:41.426 --> 00:39:43.466
performance for the test we wanted to develop.

680
00:39:44.706 --> 00:39:48.306
So we then, again, going back to those PROBE principles, wanted to

681
00:39:48.386 --> 00:39:52.256
select pre-clinical blood samples for our discovery and validation work, and we had

682
00:39:52.266 --> 00:39:56.086
the good fortune of collaborating with two cohorts, Women's Health Initiative,

683
00:39:56.186 --> 00:40:00.106
large prospective cohort of over 161,000 women, as well as the

684
00:40:00.146 --> 00:40:03.746
Cardiovascular Health Study, a much smaller cohort that focused on individuals over

685
00:40:03.766 --> 00:40:04.865
the age of 65.

686
00:40:06.046 --> 00:40:09.556
Both of these cohorts were PROBE compliant in the ways that

687
00:40:09.606 --> 00:40:13.486
they collected and stored blood samples, as well as their

688
00:40:13.526 --> 00:40:17.466
central education of breast cancer outcomes, as

689
00:40:17.526 --> 00:40:19.686
well as other available clinical data.

690
00:40:20.106 --> 00:40:23.936
So basically, what we did is we applied a nested case control study design to these

691
00:40:24.026 --> 00:40:27.966
cohorts, where we defined the cases as any woman who was

692
00:40:28.006 --> 00:40:31.986
diagnosed with a hormone receptor positive breast cancer, who

693
00:40:32.046 --> 00:40:35.596
had a blood draw within the two years prior to that cancer diagnosis.

694
00:40:35.906 --> 00:40:39.826
And then we matched controls to those cases, who were

695
00:40:40.346 --> 00:40:44.056
cancer-free women. We matched them on things like age, race, and

696
00:40:44.106 --> 00:40:44.666
geography.

697
00:40:46.426 --> 00:40:49.986
We then selected our biomarker discovery platform,

698
00:40:50.566 --> 00:40:54.326
which is this antibody microarray platform developed by my colleague, Paul

699
00:40:54.386 --> 00:40:55.306
Lampe, at Fred Hutch.

700
00:40:56.106 --> 00:40:59.906
It's a platform where we basically print 3,000 different

701
00:41:00.046 --> 00:41:02.686
antibodies on a single slide. I'm not going to go through all of the details.

702
00:41:03.446 --> 00:41:05.186
And we can use it for both

703
00:41:06.126 --> 00:41:09.326
identification of protein biomarkers, as well as autoantibody

704
00:41:09.746 --> 00:41:10.786
biomarkers.

705
00:41:11.726 --> 00:41:13.346
And so

706
00:41:14.206 --> 00:41:17.876
one of the main advantages of this particular platform is also that it requires

707
00:41:17.886 --> 00:41:21.816
very small volumes of samples. So only 25 microliters of plasma for the protein

708
00:41:22.286 --> 00:41:25.776
array, and only one microliter of plasma for the autoantibody

709
00:41:25.826 --> 00:41:29.286
array. And so we could look at both cases and controls in a pretty high throughput

710
00:41:29.366 --> 00:41:32.886
manner, looking at 3,000 protein markers and then 3,000

711
00:41:32.946 --> 00:41:36.165
autoantibody markers using these sample volumes.

712
00:41:37.326 --> 00:41:39.686
We also wanted to make sure that this was a reproducible platform.

713
00:41:39.786 --> 00:41:43.606
Here's just very quickly the coefficients of variance for the different markers

714
00:41:43.886 --> 00:41:45.846
when we looked at them in triplicate.

715
00:41:46.906 --> 00:41:47.786
And you can see that

716
00:41:48.846 --> 00:41:52.346
all the CVs are generally less than 10% and that this didn't vary by the

717
00:41:52.406 --> 00:41:54.906
abundance of the proteins.

718
00:41:56.986 --> 00:42:00.086
So, this slide actually summarizes several years of work.

719
00:42:00.606 --> 00:42:04.466
But what we wanted to do is to take all the different kind of

720
00:42:04.646 --> 00:42:08.426
sets of samples that we had and then divide them into independent sets

721
00:42:08.626 --> 00:42:12.426
of samples that we could then apply this framework

722
00:42:12.506 --> 00:42:15.176
of biomarker discovery, confirmation, and validation.

723
00:42:15.846 --> 00:42:19.626
So here you can see that we started our discovery work looking at all

724
00:42:19.786 --> 00:42:23.746
3,000 markers in the protein setting in one of

725
00:42:23.786 --> 00:42:27.376
our WHI, we call it WHI one set, where we had 121 cases,

726
00:42:27.466 --> 00:42:31.326
121 controls. We then had kind of pre-specified statistical

727
00:42:31.386 --> 00:42:35.166
criteria in terms of the sensitivity specificity that the markers needed to have in

728
00:42:35.186 --> 00:42:38.906
order to pass through to the different confirmation steps, all the way through to

729
00:42:38.966 --> 00:42:42.906
the final validation step, which was in the Cardiovascular Health Study

730
00:42:42.986 --> 00:42:45.686
sample, 65 cases, 296 controls.

731
00:42:46.666 --> 00:42:50.626
We ended up going from those 3,000 markers to 32 markers that we

732
00:42:50.646 --> 00:42:52.746
were trying to validate in the CHS set.

733
00:42:53.306 --> 00:42:57.106
We ended up validating six at P less than 0.05 and 10 at P

734
00:42:57.166 --> 00:43:00.462
less than 0.1.From this particular set.

735
00:43:01.362 --> 00:43:04.882
This is a very similar slide showing the same kind of pathway for our

736
00:43:04.942 --> 00:43:08.682
autoantibody markers. Again, started with 3,000, ended with

737
00:43:08.762 --> 00:43:12.432
12, validated five of those at P less than .05, and

738
00:43:12.522 --> 00:43:12.862
seven

739
00:43:14.362 --> 00:43:18.252
at P less than .1. So this slide

740
00:43:18.342 --> 00:43:22.302
shows you our five best markers with the performance across each

741
00:43:22.362 --> 00:43:24.102
of the three different preclinical sets.

742
00:43:24.502 --> 00:43:27.102
So two protein and three autoantibody markers.

743
00:43:27.962 --> 00:43:31.022
And you can see that all of these markers have been previously

744
00:43:31.062 --> 00:43:35.042
implicated in cancer progression, metastasis,

745
00:43:35.102 --> 00:43:38.862
or proliferation. So starting at the top, REG4

746
00:43:39.262 --> 00:43:43.162
is known to promote breast cancer stem cell properties through the

747
00:43:43.202 --> 00:43:46.182
Wnt/beta-catenin and EGFR/AKT pathways,

748
00:43:47.102 --> 00:43:51.042
and has been specifically shown to be upregulated in breast cancer and to

749
00:43:51.062 --> 00:43:52.822
promote proliferation and metastasis.

750
00:43:53.562 --> 00:43:57.542
Next is JAK2, which is known to be involved in the

751
00:43:57.582 --> 00:44:01.382
JAK-STAT signaling pathway, promotes cancer cell survival,

752
00:44:01.402 --> 00:44:05.322
proliferation, resistance to apoptosis, and also has been implicated

753
00:44:05.382 --> 00:44:07.282
in resistance to chemotherapy.

754
00:44:08.722 --> 00:44:11.812
Those kind of looking at this table very closely will see that we use 80%

755
00:44:11.842 --> 00:44:15.722
specificity rather than the 95% specificity for our

756
00:44:15.742 --> 00:44:17.662
evaluation of these individual markers.

757
00:44:17.982 --> 00:44:21.302
And this is because we never expected that one single marker would be able to

758
00:44:21.342 --> 00:44:23.562
achieve the intended performance that we had.

759
00:44:23.892 --> 00:44:26.922
And so we wanted to try to enrich the pool of markers that we had for those that

760
00:44:26.982 --> 00:44:30.502
had reasonably high specificity in the hopes that then being able to put together a

761
00:44:30.562 --> 00:44:34.142
panel of markers would enable us to achieve our desired level of

762
00:44:34.382 --> 00:44:38.162
performance. So the next step then was to try to

763
00:44:39.202 --> 00:44:42.162
integrate these markers to try to optimize the performance of the panel.

764
